text: YES! I read the entire book cover to cover in 2 days a few months ago. After reading it I had a few fears. I was afraid Matt Damon was not going to be a good Mark Watney, I was afraid they would not be able to capture the humor of the book (which for me was the best part and set the book aside from any other survival story) and I was afraid they would Hollywood it up, leaving something that bore only a passing resemblance to the book I loved so much..  This trailer has laid those fears to rest. Aside from the sign he used to contact Nasa, I could look at every scene in this trailer and tell you where it happened in the book. And while I wish I saw more funny parts from the book, I can honestly say that Matt Damon is a lot better in this role than I expected, based soley off the trailer. Can't wait.

text: It's a good point and reminder for those nutty corps that have tried sprouting up for the sake of sending people to Mars. It's a nearly doomed notion. Not only are you talking about years of travel time, you're also talking about people outside the protective shielding of our planet that we have thus far not sent people completely away from. On top of that, the risk of any number of random events causing catastrophe and that help can take years with its' own risks just to arrive. As it stands with our current technology and understanding of interplanetary travel, doing so will only result in a few bold, brave people dying far far far from home.

text: The premise of this movie is ridiculous. There is no way a dust storm's winds could be strong enough to compromise a Mission. While winds could get up to 400 km/h (250 mph), the pressure at sea level on mars is 600 pascals (.087 psi) and the pressure at sea level at earth is 101.3 kilopascals (14.69 psi). To give an earth equivalent, the effective wind speed would be a light 2.36 km/h (1.475) on Earth. This is definitely not enough to throw rocks around, as shown in the trailer. The only possible danger would be dust kicked up by the storm destroying equipment, but we have pretty thoroughly solved that sort of problem, as demonstrated by our incredibly long lasting rovers. It would be a pretty crappy mission to be taken out by that sort of thing. source: (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atmosphere_of_Mars)

text: It's about time movies started getting into space exploration while being decently produced. Was worried Interstellar was going to be the last in my lifetime. Although, even though Avatar was fiction, as was Interstellar, both did well bringing actual science to the game. Even though Avatar had much more theoretical biological science, clearly. Sound in space sadly was and still is a common plague to science fiction movies/games. Kinda kills the mood for me personally when missiles in space battles cause big flaming, smokey, explosions and then everything is on fire including the exterior of the ship. Unless the force field contains its own atmosphere, which at that point, why not just walk around on the outside of the ship without a space suit?  Whatever, the most interesting part of the movie/books to me will be/was the agricultural situation he finds himself in. As a chemistry nerd, Quick fact: the atmosphere of Mars consists of about 96% carbon dioxide. Guess what many plants on earth require to grow...????

text: Amazing looking movie...  TERRIBLE TRAILER!  A trailer ¬†is supposed to get you excited... Share the overall mood of the movie.  Not spoil key plot elements.¬†  This trailer reveals that :  1) Matt manages to stay alive longer then what the MARS "base" was intended too by growing plants   2) That he manages to send a message back to NASA  3) That his crew are turning back to get him and are likely to be the ones saving him at the end of the movie.  Was it so hard to make a simple trailer with Matt being just stuck on MARS and trying to figure out a way to survive? Was it really necessary to reveal all this stuff?  How are we suppose to feel any tension and excitement when actually watching the full movie when we already know so much about how it?  I mean... If this was like the third trailer, at least I could tell myself (Ok, already watched the teaser and first trailer. I don't need to watch more and risk being spoiled).  But this is THE FIRST TRAILER! It's not even a teaser... It's a TRAILER!  This isn't as bad as the latest terminator trailers, but still... They should find a guy who understands that trailers are not supposed to give away major spoilers and stick with him when it comes to making trailers.  The only way the movie can surprise me at this point is if Matt ends up building his own freaking spaceship to get off mars or that aliens come and save him... which are both unlikely.  I am still going to see it, but the trailer is likely to ruin a good half of the excitement I could get out of this movie.

text: Like all Hollywood sci-fi this movie gets all the science completely wrong. The atmosphere on Mars is 100 times thinner than Earth's, so even in the fiercest dust storm an astronaut would hardly feel it, it would be a very mild buffetting sensation. The plot will start from a ridiculous premise and swiftly descend into absurdly farcical rubbish with more plot holes than you can count until it ends in a totally unbelievable way. It would make a change to have a science fiction movie in which the science wasn't totally ignored in favour of sensationalist over-the-top effects.

text: EDIT!! [Jun. 19] Reading only the first part of this post may communicate (sometimes very strongly) something other than what I'm saying. So please, set aside responding to felt offense until after having read (not skim) the whole thing. Thank you. <><><><>  I'm a Psychology major, having taken multiple classes in psychology, participated in labs, interact with my professors, and overall study the science. As such, I can tell you:  --- If there is anything that science has shown us, it is that `helping others` is NOT a base instinct. What IS our base instinct is `wanting to be right` and `wanting to be liked`.  Sometimes this manifests as helping others in danger. Sometimes this manifests as punching that jerk in the face. And retaliating to being hurt by hurting back is much, MUCH more common, and more immediate a desire; it is instinctual.  We want to believe that we're good on an instinctual level, but this can only be believed in blind faith. We don't even need psychology to prove the opposite. Our every experience of wanting to respond to being hurt by hurting back proves that our instincts will destroy us.  We all know this. However, we want to deny it.  For some people, the message behind this movie will make it easier to believe that we are "mostly good". However, that will ensnare some people, making it harder for them to break the addiction to thinking themselves "mostly good", which leads to confusion and mental suffering. I am intimately aware of this in my own past and in the lives of many others.  Let's help one another! Let's try to save people in danger, and heal people who are hurting. Let us fight our natural instinct -- which is `hurting back` -- and instead forgive each other. We don't need this blind faith in ourselves in order to do good. That's a cop-out, and can trap hurting people where they are, keeping them from seeking out the help that they need.  What we need to do, is choose to love.  And when it gets too hard to love, let your weakness prove your need for strength from outside yourself, and go seek it out.  "Come to me, all who labor and are heavy laden, and I will give you rest. Take my yoke upon you, and learn from me, for I am gentle and lowly in heart, and you will find rest for your souls. For my yoke is easy, and my burden is light." -- Jesus, in Matthew 11:28-30

text: life long sci fi fan (and therefore space exploration) I love Asimov and Clarke (though clearly not some of Clarke's alleged habits) I read a number of years ago several books by Kim Stanley Robinson, about the terraforming of Mars, whilst interesting if a bit long one of the things he did (like Dune) was take a long view of things, I have always had an issue with either fact or fiction that a manned "Mars Shot" would be a one shot deal, What I mean to say is that if you are going to send a group of people of world, there are inherent dangers not just when they get to point X but in the flight, micro asteroids, solar flares etc, so surely it would be more apropos to send several ships with overlapping capabilities and equipment, that said i'm in the front of the queue for this film

Thirdly, I felt as though "Interstellar" was kind of a let down. text: I am really looking forward to watching this movie. I have always been a fan of Matt Damon, and his first take as an astronaut alongside the central character that Jessica Chastain portrayed in "Interstellar" highly impressed me. Here, "The Martian" pairs them for a second time, with Damon again playing a central role as a stranded astronaut alone on a planet millions of miles from Earth. With Jeff Daniels, Sean Bean, Danny Glover, Kate Mara, and Kristen Wiig rounding out the team under the direction of the original outer space filmmaking master Ridley Scott, both the proven cast and Director together legitimize high expectations for a terrific, smart, suspenseful journey into the Unknown.

text: One of the greatest challenges for any manned Mars mission isn't surviving the planet itself, but remaining mentally sound on the way there -- you don't want to freak out during a months-long space voyage. And it looks like the producers behind the movie adaptation of The Martian are well aware of this practical reality. They've posted a teaser clip showing how the fictional NASA crew copes with 10 days of isolation training meant to simulate the disconnection they'll likely experience during the journey. As you'll see below, some of them handle it better than others. A few are practically itching to go on the expedition, while others clearly... suffered a bit. Why does Aquaman have control over whales?

text: One of the best, and worst, aspects of the book was that Marc was so cute and funny (he could be because everything was written after the fact in his journal logs) that it kind of deflated any tension or emotion the film could build. From the trailer, it looks like this film may have solved a lot of these problems. We see shots of Marc, the crew, and Jeff Daniels (Venkat? Talk about white-washing) all looking forlorn and scared which helps provide weight and illustrates how impossible the mission is. It also looks like the airlock scene is kept in the film where his helmet cracks. That might be the best scene. I also hope they do a montage where Marc tricks out the rover to the song 'Stayin' Alive', but then the montage ends when he shorts out the pathfinder.  Also, I imagined the Hab and Hermes to be a fraction of the size this trailer shows them to be.

The story began back in 2007 when consumables invented story about the Russian astronaut in distress during a tornado suddenly erupted on Mars. In 2008 and 2009, the writer introduces the concept of the project the largest Russian and international companies. And he believes that's when the story hit Andy Uiru, author of "The Martian". In May 2011, we began filming the scenario Raskhodnikova that ended in August 2012. The truth is this film for some reason on the screens has not yet been released.  Then, in 2012, in the United States published a book "The Martian", written by the author debutant Andy Weir, and Drew Goddard which created the script for the new film by Ridley Scott. "When I read this book for me was the obvious similarities, because the entire outline of the plot and the characters are very similar," - said Mikhail consumables.  Lawyers film company 20th Century Fox have assured that Weir had never been to Russia, does not speak Russian and did not see the script Raskhodnikova. text: Why shouldn't NASA have to offer Mars prizes, rewarding (for example) the first companies that successfully send and return humans to Mars? It could be done via:  ChallengeDOTgov  All sorts of Mars-related breakthroughs lend themselves to pro-entrepreneurial Mars prizes, but NASA's (predictably) not offering them. Why not?  Unfortunately NASA's a monopolistic, jealous govt. bureaucracy that feeds off of nearly $20 billion of our tax dollars per year. Its "workers" make load$ of money achieving relatively little, and they don't want to upset the apple cart. Innovation's needed though, due to the USA's bankruptcy:  usdebtclockDOTorg   The status quo isn't getting us to Mars for way too long, and they keep postponing the promised humans-to-Mars date too... The bureaucracy is parasitizing and will continue to do so until we demand better ways of spending our space exploration-related tax dollars. Are you up for demanding change?

text: I watched it last night.  DON'T read unless you don't mind SPOILERS             Trailer showed too much?  :   Yes it showed way too much  I enjoyed few of the director's movies but this wasn't one of them. First of all..  You are in Mars all alone and I mean.. psychologically,  Mark Watney did not suffer anything.  One rage was enough for him. I think it makes him a robot.. Everything was great but I was expecting more of suspense and thrill that you could see in Christopher Nolan movies. But this was like.. so light. Remember Cast Away?  wow..  comparing to that, this guy Mark Watney must be a robot. This fact ruined the whole movie for me.. All the feelings that we could have felt with Mark Watney was just gone with some lame disco musics. It was not comedy and it certainly was not suspense movie  ( like interstellar ). And really..really bad choice of background music... Well..  This was just my own opinion and I am a bit biased to Christopher Nolan movies so I might offend some youtubers and I apologize. but it is just my opinion. If you wanted to see something like Interstellar  then wait till it goes to DVD.
